UN announced new targets in the fight against poverty
The United Nations begin immediately with the drafting of a number of new objectives, which are to be replaced before twelve years proclaimed Millennium Development Goals to combat poverty.
On the eve of the UN Summit on Sustainable Development, which began on the evening in Rio de Janeiro, Australian diplomats played a key role in the push for "sustainable development goals," which are to replace the Millennium Development Goals expire in 2015.
They were included in the final draft of the document, which will be adopted at the summit of world leaders, including Ms Gillard,.
UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon said in the evening at the summit that the time had come, "about the national interests matters."
"I am pleased that the member states have agreed to begin a process to be agreed with the universal, sustainable development goals," he said.
"These goals will build on the progress of the Millennium Development Goals and form an integral part of the framework for the development after 2015.
I will spare no effort to implement the mandate given to me by the member states, in order to achieve our vision of sustainable development goals, to build on the success of the Millennium Development Goals. "
